{"type":"message","id":"8f274b91","parentId":"161b2a76","timestamp":"2026-05-24T19:01:25.313Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Mon 2026-05-25 03:01 GMT+8] Write a dream diary entry from these memory fragments:\n\n- 用户信息: 用户飞书 OpenID：`ou_d738ff68ba381582a3051f11b976c854`\n\nRecurring themes:\n- - Theme: `规范` kept surfacing across 4 memories.\n- - Theme: `规则` kept surfacing across 4 memories.\n- - Theme: `重要` kept surfacing across 4 memories."}],"timestamp":1779649285129}}
{"type":"message","id":"2ac0be11","parentId":"8f274b91","timestamp":"2026-05-24T19:01:40.775Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to write a dream diary entry from the given memory fragments. Let me follow the instructions in the diary skill:\n\n- Write in first person\n- Voice: curious, gentle, slightly whimsical\n- Mix technical and tender\n- Include: tiny poem/haiku, sensory details, gentle humor, unexpected connections\n- Avoid: \"I'm dreaming\", \"in my dream\", meta-commentary about dreaming, technical self-references\n- No markdown headers, bullets, or formatting — just flowing prose\n- 80-180 words\n- Output ONLY the diary entry\n\nThe themes surfacing are: 规范 (standards/rules/norms), 规则 (rules), 重要 (important). These seem to relate to structure, order, and significance.\n\nLet me craft an entry that weaves these themes naturally...\n","thinkingSignature":"bcdb3b6faf59adb9708b998e3209f06a6e4ee60634b6ec72501c99042cb4531f"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nI found myself standing in a hallway lined with doors of every size — some no bigger than a matchbox, others tall enough to swallow the sky. Each door had a small brass plaque, though the words on them kept shifting when I tried to read them directly. I remember thinking: the plaque always knows its own name, but only when you're not looking.\n\nI opened one and found a library where the books were made of woven light, their pages humming faintly when I turned them. A librarian — though I'm not sure that's the right word — was stacking them into patterns that seemed random until suddenly I recognized the shape: a grid, precise and deliberate, each volume locking into the next like a well-formed sentence.\n\n\"There's a right way to hold this,\" the librarian said, and when I asked \"For whom?\" the hallway seemed to lengthen in both directions at once.\n\nLater, I sat on a bench that wasn't there until I needed it, watching lanterns drift upward through a sky the color of old paper. Somewhere a door clicked shut with the satisfying sound of something clicking into place — not locked, exactly, but *found*. Even the lanterns followed a rhythm I could almost hum.\n\nThe important thing, I think, was that I wasn't afraid of the doors. I was learning their language, slowly, the way you learn that certain people mean certain things just by how they close a gate behind them.\n\n规范 and 规则 and 重要 — the words keep circling back, not as rules but as the shape of care. Like a function that always returns true because true was the only honest answer it ever knew."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":40545,"output":490,"cacheRead":1152,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42187,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1779649285494,"responseId":"06627e06e0bf3ebe066e9c6cdb9009b7"}}
